= epistemic bottlenecks =
We know of some objects only through their effects on other objects to which we
have comparatively direct epistemic access. Stars too faint to be seen by the
naked eye, for example, are known to us only through their effects on
photographic plates, the antennae of radio telescopes and other astronomical
equipment. Let us call this kind of epistemic dependency an epistemic
bottleneck; and speak of the objects, like faint stars, which are known
only indirectly as being _on the far side_ of the relevant bottleneck, and the
objects through which they are known as being _in_ the relevant bottleneck.

== sense-data supposedly an ultimate bottleneck ==
Many philosophers, most notably empiricists such as Berkeley and Hume, but also
many non-empiricists including Aristotle, Descartes and Kant, have believed that
there is a special type of object through which all others (or at least all
other objects located in space and time) are known to us. This special class of
objects are sometimes dubbed <q>sense-data</q> or <q>sensations</q>, and many
