, and that we only know of other objects (or at least other
objects located in space and time) through their effects on these sense-data. If
there are such sense-data they constitute a kind of ultimate epistemic
bottleneck, on the far side of which were all the other objects in the world.
The claim that there are epistemic bottlenecks, however, does not commit us to
the existence of such an ultimate bottleneck nor the existence of sense data.
Even if there is no ultimate epistemic bottleneck nor ultimate evidence upon
which all our knowledge of a posteriori truths is based, and what is taken as
evidence depends on context and passing interests, there may still be
non-ultimate epistemic bottlenecks.

Although belief in sense-data is no longer as widespread as it was, it may
be worthwhile to note several other properties that have traditionally been
attributed to sense-data which are not required of the objects in epistemic
bottlenecks as that term is being defined here:

==== need not be directly observed ====
The objects in one epistemic bottleneck, may themselves be on the far side of
some other epistemic bottleneck, and known only by their effects on yet closer
objects to which our epistemic access is again _comparatively_ more direct.

In Russell's terminology the objects in an epistemic bottleneck need not be
<q>known by acquaintance</q> but may
be <q>known by description</q>. But the existence of epistemic
bottlenecks, or rather of objects in epistemic bottlenecks, does not presume on
Russell's theory of knowledge.  Indeed the existence of epistemic bottlenecks
does not imply that there are any epistemically closest objects that are known
to us by acquaintance at all.

The claim that there are epistemic bottlenecks does not preclude there being
proximal _causes_ of experience without proximal objects _of_ experience.  Our
awareness may always be of more or less distal objects((Least distal are those objects which directly impinge upon our skin or other sensory surfaces, and the firing of our sensory cells themselves. In psychological texts these are sometime described as proximal stimuli which are <q>directly perceived by our sensory receptors</q>. But of course such events are not directly perceived by _us_ and are not known to us by acquaintance.  By that rigorous standard such impingements still count as distal and there is a sense in which the firing of our sensory cells is not perceived by us at all except with the aid of special equipment (and generally in the third person). Let us avoid being drawn into just where to draw the line between proximal and distal stimuli for the time being.)). If we perceive
apples, chairs and people without there being intermediary sense-data which we
perceive directly, that does not preclude the existence of epistemic
bottlenecks.

==== known infallibly, only a simplifying assumption ====
Another special property many philosophers have attributed to sense-data
